    </div>

    <main>
      <p>Music has always been the undercurrent of my life‚Äîsometimes loud and brash, sometimes quiet and grounding, but always there.</p>
      <p>As a little kid, I was constantly singing: in the car, to myself, to anyone who would listen. My mom blasted Carole King‚Äôs <em>Tapestry</em> in her little Yugo, filling our rides with the ache of ‚ÄúSo Far Away.‚Äù My brother Jimmy made sure the whole house knew he was going to <em>fight for his right to party</em>‚Äîblasting Beastie Boys and N.W.A. until the walls shook. My sister and I choreographed Lisa Loeb‚Äôs <em>Stay</em> on the jungle gym, convinced we were destined for Olympic floor routines. Music wasn‚Äôt just entertainment; it was oxygen.</p>
      <p>High school cemented that bond. I ruled the band and choir rooms. Jazz Band mornings gave me peace; Swing Choir gave me sparkle. A trip to Toronto gave me the surreal joy of seeing Paul Stanley from KISS as the Phantom. And in an almost comical oversight, our small-town Wisconsin high school took us to see <em>RENT</em>‚Äîwhich cracked my ideas about what a musical could be. Rock. Grit. Modern storytelling. I wanted more.</p>
      <p>I sang at the Dorian Vocal Festival. By senior year, I walked away with the National School Choral Award <em>and</em> the John Philip Sousa Award‚Äîproof that the practice room hours mattered.</p>
      <p>College tried to nudge me ‚Äúpractical.‚Äù Biotech major, D in Biology. I pivoted to music‚Äîtheory, dictation, voice, piano (badly), history‚Äîand found another mic: the college radio station. <em>The Blonde Moment</em> was born, spinning Ani and Nelly, taking requests from dorms and even the county jail. Somewhere there‚Äôs a cassette of that show waiting to be rescued before it disintegrates.</p>
      <p>In 2006, a coworker mentioned the Madison Opera Chorus. Within months, I was on stage, stretched further than ever. Eight operas later‚Äîincluding <em>Carmen</em> while pregnant with Porter‚Äîmy life had a new kind of downbeat.</p>
      <p>Now my pulse is a mixtape: Tori, Ani, Alanis, Fiona‚Äîand yes, Taylor. Her words sharpened with age and healing: <em>‚ÄúYou‚Äôre on your own, kid.‚Äù</em> <em>‚ÄúI was a functioning alcoholic ‚Äôtil nobody noticed my new aesthetic.‚Äù</em> Therapy in glitter.</p>
      <p>Peek at my playlists and you‚Äôll hear ADHD in stereo: House of Pain‚Äôs <em>Jump Around</em> slamming into Taylor‚Äôs <em>Bejeweled</em>, then straight into ‚ÄúI‚Äôm the queen of the castle‚Äù from <em>Six</em>. Chaos. Joy. Me.</p>
      <p><strong>And tonight</strong>‚Äîit comes full circle. Ani DiFranco again, but this time with Porter. They‚Äôre drawn to Ani as an artist, a feminist, an activist, a truth-teller. I can‚Äôt wait for them to feel that spark live, in a room that knows music can be both rebellion and refuge.</p>
      <p>Music has always been my safe place, my rallying cry, and the reminder that our voices matter.</p>

